<subSubSection id="1600181CDBCAC9DCE73730D2BFCC4C3D" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" type="ecology">
<paragraph id="2AFA6C173B44B4244548B2BDBD90B1CC" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
<pageBreakToken id="690B11CCEE9F96581E4D02F0D2BBE2C3" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" start="start">Ecology</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D2B2FD41A12F842E1C9F191059B975E8" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
Known from a single wild population on a small and unnamed island near Island Bay. Here it grows in open and disturbed areas among petrel burrows and 
<taxonomicName id="A846D4A379ABEF5E8B685D8809BCB0E4" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Aizoaceae" genus="Disphyma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="australe">
<emphasis id="C6E96B13E0EFFC4C059D4796F6B37A51" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Disphyma australe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(W.I.Aiton) N.E.Br. subsp. 
<emphasis id="86285A1087C2C5073216637B1CE10604" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">australe</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="0EB6A7B735A8A27D08144C412F3EB2D0" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Cauline leaves of (A) Lepidium oligodontum - variation within a single plant, (B) Lepidium oligodontum - variation amongst plants from different locations: (left to right) The Sisters, Western Reef, Point Somes, Moriori Creek, Star Keys, Rangatira Island, Antipodes Island. (C) Lepidium panniforme, (D) Lepidium rekohuense. Scale bars = 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10744" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Additional populations of 
<taxonomicName id="9F834C0B2D0A2349B934DB08CA74D753" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegrum">
<emphasis id="74958C56B55017F759D9D4EB008022B7" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">Lepidium aegrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been established in Canterbury on 
<pageBreakToken id="F35E3BC2FD982733A8C7A353287C09D3" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" start="start">Motunau</pageBreakToken>
Island (Pegasus Bay), Quail Island (Lyttleton Harbour), and at Stony Bay (Banks Peninsula).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="352C57D5FD721057FC85E632471CB65F" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="9A3357FA039061E18848FAB4D7F61336" bold="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Recognition.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="2A6E59ACC00449723363D8156EB1B31E" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegrum">
<emphasis id="D93839AB62214D3C05C023F5B0D43282" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Lepidium aegrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished by its slender flexible stems (
<figureCitation id="7EBBFC731605D8120E27D32CEFD4F1BF" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="F11" captionText="Figure 11. Lepidium aegrum stem showing four inflorescences. Scale bar = 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10749" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Figs 11</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="DB409472731146ADB00CEBE1FA62213F" captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Lepidium aegrum leafy stems showing mid-stem and apical foliage. Scale bar = 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10750" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">12</figureCitation>
), light green membranous leaves that are lanceolate, elliptic-lanceolate or narrowly elliptic with a prominent acute to subacute apex, and margins that are serrate with prominent and deep teeth (
<figureCitation id="B2692C9390EF4550CDE1EA94EF140E08" captionStart="Figure 13" captionStartId="F13" captionText="Figure 13. Lepidium aegrum (from left to right) basal- to mid-stem foliage. Scale bar = 20 mm." httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/10751" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="47DE1C7931461B8E06BE173FF9E215D5" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">
<emphasis id="A9229340B0DE1EF23814CD7CCCD10A42" bold="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Conservation Status.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="560EBD14A07EA3F9B2C0CAE6767058E2" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegrum">
<emphasis id="88B794D23D70CEFCD15C295A934449E2" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Lepidium aegrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from a single wild population and three additional populations that have been established with nursery-raised plants. The single wild population and unknown recruitment patterns means that this species is especially vulnerable to stochastic events. Furthermore, turnip mosiac virus, which deforms and retards growth, is common in plants at the wild population, and this will likely reduce reproductive success (
<bibRefCitation id="40AA7B7B9FFC2F557A49C19DBDD2A767" author="Fletcher, JD" journalOrPublisher="New Zealand Bird Notes" pageId="113" pageNumber="114" refId="B39" refString="Fletcher, JD, Bulman, S, Fletcher, PJ, Houliston, GJ, 2009. First record of Turnip mosaic virus in Cooks scurvy grass (Lepidium oleraceum agg). An endangered native plant in New Zealand. Australasian Plant Disease notes4: 9-11. doi.org/10.1071/DN09004." title="First record of Turnip mosaic virus in Cooks scurvy grass (Lepidium oleraceum agg). An endangered native plant in New Zealand. Australasian Plant Disease notes 4: 9 - 11. doi. org / 10.1071 / DN 09004" year="2009">Fletcher et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). Using the New Zealand Threat Classification System (
<bibRefCitation id="712F80CD8BC0A53F4365EC2050D2011F" author="Townsend, AJ" journalOrPublisher="Bioinformatics" pageId="116" pageNumber="117" refId="B86" refString="Townsend, AJ, de Lange, PJ, Norton, DA, Molloy, J, Miskelly, C, Duffy, C, 2008. The New Zealand Threat Classification System manual. Department of Conservation: Wellington. http://www.doc.govt.nz/publications/conservation/nz-threat-classification-system/nz-threat-classification-system-manual-2008/." title="The New Zealand Threat Classification System manual. Department of Conservation: Wellington. http: // www. doc. govt. nz / publications / conservation / nz-threat-classification-system / nz-threat-classification-system-manual- 2008 /" year="2008">Townsend et al. 2008</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="9783FB47F39C7C9E6968D7CFCE022FB1" authorityName="Lange &amp; Heenan &amp; Houliston &amp; Rolfe &amp; Mitchell" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Hesperiidae" genus="Lepidium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="20" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aegrum">
<emphasis id="A742C81DAD0A48C4C4D67BE820EB56CA" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="20">Lepidium aegrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
qualifies as Threatened/Nationally Critical. We recommend appending the qualifiers 
<normalizedToken id="97BBC767C4CD9CE39EC1C9107B554D64" originalValue="‘CD’">'CD'</normalizedToken>
(Conservation Dependent - as it has been established and is being managed at Motunau and Quail islands, and at Stony Bay), 
<normalizedToken id="FA732B538FB030AB62169F3DF7F82181" originalValue="‘DP’">'DP'</normalizedToken>
(Data Poor - to reflect uncertainty over plant numbers and population trends), 
<normalizedToken id="07F84AD73E050BA6284867D35620B5D7" originalValue="‘OL’">'OL'</normalizedToken>
(One location - since it is known from a single wild population).
</paragraph>
